03848nam a2200493Ia 9780791478684DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97807914786847 a10.1515/97807914786842doi  a(DE-B1597)683567  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aEDU0200002bisacsh1 aHondo, Carolyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLatino Dropouts in Rural America :bRealities and Possibilities /cYolanda M. Sapien, Carolyn Hondo, Mary E. Gardiner. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (198 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 3  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe High School Dropout Phenomenon -- tResearch Methods -- tInside Three Rural Schools and Communities -- tCase Studies -- tCase Studies -- tComposite Analysis -- tA Leadership Plan for Culturally Responsive Schools -- tReferences -- tA Phenomenology -- tInterview Guides -- tRecommendations for Superintendents and Policy Makers -- tRecommendations for Superintendents and Policy Makers -- tResources for Culturally Responsive Teaching and Leadership -- tProfessional Development Activities for Cultural Responsiveness -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book affords Latino high school dropouts from rural communities in Idaho the opportunity to tell their stories in their own words. It candidly reveals students' school experiences, explores why students leave school, and looks at the impact of the No Child Left Behind Act (2001). Four of the nine students interviewed for the book passed NCLB-mandated state graduation tests, two others passed two of three sections, and all were capable of achieving success in school. The decision to leave school was connected with students' seeking personal satisfaction and to reduce the social-psychological pain of schooling. In certain cases principals and teachers blamed the Latino students for disadvantaging the school. Latino Dropouts in Rural America presents a systematic approach for addressing the main problem: a lack of cultural responsiveness in school curriculum, instruction, policies, and practices. The leadership plan recommended by the authors will help educators to understand the lives of rural Latino youth and to critique their own schools.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aEducation : Curriculum. 7aEDUCATION / Multicultural Education.2bisacsh1 aGanas, Con cariñoy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner, Mary E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSapien, Yolanda M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147868440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791478684423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791478684/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles